        output='The prospectus clearly distinguishes Starlink’s consumer broadband service from its satellite-to-mobile offering. Below are the key disclosures regarding their differences, including intended use cases, performance specifications, and technical evolution.\n\n### Fundamental Design Difference\nThe two systems are explicitly separated by purpose and architecture:\n> “Our broadband satellites are designed to deliver high-speed internet services to homes, businesses, and vehicles, while our mobile satellites are designed to connect directly to cell phones from space. These constellations have different performance requirements and technical specifications.”  \n*(Prospectus Summary, glossary of satellite terms)*\n\n### Current Service Capabilities and Bandwidth\n\n**Starlink Consumer Broadband**  \n- Provides “fiber-like download speeds—at a median of 225 Mbps during peak hours for residential users as of March 31, 2026.”  \n- Median latency is “approximately 25 milliseconds,” low enough for “intensive real-time applications, such as content streaming, video calls, and online gaming.”  \n- Enterprise and mobility solutions (aviation, maritime) can deliver “download speeds exceeding 400 Mbps with round-trip latencies as low as 21 milliseconds.”  \n\n**Satellite-to-Mobile (Starlink Mobile)**  \n- The current V1 Mobile satellites offer **light data, text messaging (SMS), and over-the-top voice services** (e.g., WhatsApp, FaceTime) directly to standard, unmodified LTE handsets.  \n- “We also provide satellite-to-mobile texting and over-the-top voice services to approximately 7.4 million monthly unique devices across approximately 30 countries.”  \n- No broadband data speeds are quoted for the current mobile service—it is explicitly a “light data” and messaging service, designed to “substantially reduc[e] mobile dead zones.”\n\n### Planned Evolution and Future Bandwidth\n- **V3 Broadband Satellites:** Next-generation satellites “designed to offer one Tbps of downlink capacity per satellite,” deployable via Starship, with a single launch delivering up to 60 satellites and a “twenty-fold increase in Starlink downlink capacity” compared to a Falcon 9 launch.  \n- **V2 Mobile Satellites:** The next-generation mobile satellites “are designed to provide more comprehensive satellite-to-mobile services, including **broadband data and IoT connectivity**.” Together with the EchoStar spectrum acquisition and optimized 5G protocols, these satellites “are expected to increase capacity by orders of magnitude compared to our first-generation constellation.”\n\n### Use Case Differences\n- **Broadband use cases:** Fixed residential, small/medium business, enterprise (construction, agriculture, retail, hospitality, aviation, maritime, land mobility), and government. The service requires a Starlink user terminal (Standard, Mini, or Performance) but can support in-motion connectivity up to 100 mph and global oceanwide coverage.  \n- **Mobile use cases:** Direct-to-smartphone connectivity with no additional hardware; eliminating mobile dead zones; emergency communications during natural disasters; supplemental coverage for mobile network operators (MNOs) in remote areas. The mobile service is positioned as an extension of terrestrial cellular networks, not a replacement for fixed broadband.\n\nIn summary, Starlink Broadband is a high-throughput, low-latency internet service for homes and enterprises using dedicated terminals, while Starlink Mobile is a direct-to-phone service currently offering narrowband messaging and voice, with a roadmap toward broadband data and IoT through future satellite generations.',
