2026-06-10 00:15:05,915 DEBUG Tool call: submit_final_result({'final_result': '## Users-per-Satellite Ratios (as of March 31, 2026)\n\n### Starlink Broadband Network\n\n| Metric | Value |\n|---|---|\n| Broadband satellites (incl. mobile) | ~9,600 |\n| Starlink Subscribers | ~10.3M |\n| **Subscribers per satellite** | **~1,073** |\n\n**Calculation:** 10,300,000 ÷ 9,600 = **1,072.92 subscribers per satellite**\n\n*Nuance:* The S-1 discloses ~9,600 as "Starlink broadband and mobile satellites" combined; a separate passage notes that consumer broadband alone is enabled by "approximately 9,000 broadband satellites." Using 9,000 would yield ~1,144 subscribers per satellite. The question\'s framing of "9,600 broadband satellites" is used for this calculation consistent with the instructions.\n\n---\n\n### Starlink Mobile (V1) Network\n\n| Metric | Value |\n|---|---|\n| V1 Mobile satellites | ~650 |\n| Monthly unique satellite-to-mobile devices | ~7.4M |\n| **Monthly unique devices per satellite** | **~11,385** |\n\n**Calculation:** 7,400,000 ÷ 650 = **11,384.62 monthly unique devices per satellite**\n\n---\n\n### Ratio Comparison\n\nThe mobile network carries approximately **10.6×** more users per satellite than the broadband network (11,385 vs. 1,073).\n\n---\n\n## Utilization Implications\n\n### 1. Fundamentally Different Service Profiles\n\nThe 10.6× disparity is not a signal of relative efficiency or underutilization—it reflects two entirely different network architectures serving qualitatively different use cases:\n\n- **Starlink Broadband** delivers high-throughput, continuous connectivity: median **225 Mbps during peak hours**, ~25 ms latency, supporting streaming, video calls, and online gaming. Each subscriber\'s user terminal maintains a persistent, bandwidth-intensive connection. The constellation\'s cumulative downlink capacity exceeds **700 Tbps**, implying ~68 Mbps of average capacity per subscriber across the footprint (though capacity is not evenly distributed geographically).\n\n- **Starlink Mobile (V1)** provides narrowband services: **SMS texting, light data, and over-the-top voice** (WhatsApp, FaceTime) directly to unmodified LTE handsets. These are inherently intermittent, low-bandwidth interactions—a device may connect only for seconds to transmit a text message. No broadband data speeds are quoted for V1 Mobile service.\n\n### 2. Coverage vs. Throughput Paradigms\n\nThe broadband network operates on a **throughput-constrained** model: each satellite\'s finite downlink capacity must be shared among concurrent subscribers, and adding subscribers without adding capacity degrades service. The ~1,073 subscribers-per-satellite ratio reflects an equilibrium where SpaceX can maintain its advertised median 225 Mbps peak-hour performance.\n\nThe mobile network operates on a **coverage-constrained** model: the primary value proposition is eliminating "dead zones" by providing any connectivity at all. Because each device consumes minimal airtime, a single V1 Mobile satellite can serve thousands of unique devices per month without congestion. The ~11,385 devices-per-satellite ratio measures reach and coverage density, not capacity utilization.\n\n### 3. Distinction Between "Subscribers" and "Monthly Unique Devices"\n\nThe two metrics are not directly comparable in economic terms. "Starlink Subscribers" are paying customers with dedicated hardware terminals. "Monthly unique devices" count any handset that connected to the mobile network during the month—potentially including non-paying users (e.g., emergency connectivity, free-tier service through MNO partnerships). This further explains the higher device-per-satellite figure on the mobile side.\n\n### 4. Growth Trajectory and Capacity Expansion\n\nBoth networks are scaling. Over 3,000 satellites were deployed in 2025 alone. The next-generation **V3 broadband satellites** are designed for **1 Tbps downlink capacity per satellite** (vs. the current fleet average of ~73 Mbps per satellite, based on 700 Tbps ÷ 9,600). A single Starship launch can deploy up to 60 V3 satellites—a potential 20× increase in downlink capacity per launch versus Falcon 9. On the mobile side, **V2 Mobile satellites** are designed to add broadband data and IoT connectivity, increasing capacity "by orders of magnitude."\n\n### 5. Key Analytical Takeaway\n\nThe users-per-satellite ratios for the two networks should not be compared as if they measure the same thing. The broadband ratio (~1,073) reflects a capacity-sharing constraint for a high-bandwidth service; the mobile ratio (~11,385) reflects coverage reach for a narrowband service. The mobile network can sustain far higher device counts per satellite precisely because per-device data consumption is orders of magnitude lower. As V2 Mobile satellites introduce broadband data, the mobile users-per-satellite ratio would be expected to compress toward levels more analogous to the broadband network.'})
